    Parking Space Group Model ¶

    id
    string (optional) Example: 1644c5dc-4c5c-11e4-a24a-d43d7eecedd2

    unique identifier of the location used for referencing.

    type
    string (optional) Example: off-street

    Choices: off-street park-and-ride professional-garage airport-parking harbor-parking

    describes the type of location and can be one of the following.

    description
    string (optional) Example: Doppelparkplatz. Jedoch nur für ein Auto zu vermieten.

    image_urls
    array Example: [https://parku.de/images/parkingspace/020a81f5-c8b9-11e4-bfd2-d43d7eece658/640x286.jpg]

    urls of location images, can be empty

    options
    array Example: [excess length]

    May Contain: excess length indoor disabled patio barrier charging station key_necessary long_term_booking surveillance valet_service

    describes which options are available at the location and can contains each of the following elements. The list can be empty.

    support
    object 

    support.phone_number
    string (optional) Example: +493012064329

    returns the support center phone number for this location

    price
    object 

    price.total
    number (optional) Example: 150

    the total price for booking a parking space of this group if start and end was provided, null otherwise.

    price.currency
    string (optional) Example: EUR

    Choices: EUR CHF

    the currency of the price

    price.period
    string (optional) Example: timeframe

    Choices: timeframe day week month

    contains the period for how long the price is valid, can be null if start or end was not provided

    price.rate_hourly
    number (optional) Example: 10

    shows the price for per hour

    price.rate_daily
    number (optional) Example: 100

    shows the price per day

    price.rate_weekly
    number (optional) Example: 300

    shows the price per week

    price.rate_monthly
    number (optional) Example: 1500

    shows the price per month

    user_owned
    boolean (optional) Example: false

    true if the user who requested the location is also the owner of the parking space. This allows to determine if the user could block the parking space from bookings.

    settings
    object 

    provides booking requirements for the location. The settings of a location are used in favor of the global settings that can be found in the settings endpoint.

    settings.bookable_range_start
    number (optional) Example: -15

    start of the range wherein a booking is allowed in minutes from now.

    settings.bookable_range_end
    number (optional) Example: 43200

    end of the range wherein a booking is allowed in minutes from now. end of the range wherein a booking is allowed in minutes from now.

    settings.booking_duration_min
    number (optional) Example: 30

    minimum duration of a booking in minutes.

    settings.booking_duration_max
    number (optional) Example: 43200

    maximum duration of a booking in minutes.

    required_fields
    array Example: [car_registration_number]

    May Contain: car_registration_number car_make car_model car_colour number_of_passengers car_dropoff_time car_pickup_time outbound_flight_terminal outbound_flight_number inbound_flight_number outbound_flight_time inbound_flight_time user_mobile_number ship_name pier_name child_seat_required additional_services inbound_flight_terminal

    lists all additionally required fields when creating a booking for this location, can be empty if no fields are required. The field names correspond to the booking.fields.* entries in the settings endpoint which can be used for retrieving translated strings for these fields.

    provider
    string (optional) Example: parku

    Choices: parku holidayextras inrix

    names the parking space provider. Additional information(terms and conditions, logo, …) about the provider can found be using the provider key from the field in settings

    availability
    object 

    describes the availability of the group in relation to the requestdescribes the

    availability of the group in relation to the request

    availability.current
    number (optional) Example: 0

    the number of parking spaces available in the group for the requested time period defined

    by start and endthe number of parking spaces available in the group for the requested time period defined by start and end

    availability.maximum
    number (optional) Example: 1

    the overall number of parking spaces at this group the overall number of parking spaces at

    this group

    availability.next_start
    string (optional) Example: 2016-...15:00:..

    the start of the next from now slot in which a parking space in this

    group is free and bookable, can be in the past

    availability.next_end
    string (optional) Example: 2016-...15:00:..

    the end of the next slot from now in which a parking space in this group

    is free and bookable, can be in the past

    Availability Model Example
    {
  "current": 0,
  "maximum": 1,
  "next_start": "2016-...15:00:..",
  "next_end": "2016-...15:00:.."
}

    by start and endthe number of parking spaces available in the group for the requested time period defined by start and end

    maximum

    this group

    --insecure \
    --user 012345678abcdef:parku
    Headers
    Authorization: Basic MDEyMzQ1Njc4YWJjZGVmOnBhcmt1

    Location was not found, check the location id and that your user has the correct access rights to see the location.

    Request validation failed because the request data was malformed.

    Retrieve a Location ¶
    GET/locations/{location_id}{?date_start,date_end}

    URI Parameters
    location_id
    uuid rfc4122 (required) Example: 00cd7cfd-e42d-11e2-8bf1-8a83f3373875

    Identifier of the location.

    date_start
    string (required) Example: 2016

    10-27T09:10:20+00:00 (ISO 8601, optional) - Used to calculate the price for a location. Requires the field date_end to be defined. If no date_start or date_end is specified, the returned price field will be null.

    date_end
    string (required) Example: 2016

    10-27T10:10:20+00:00 (ISO 8601, optional) see date_start.

    Example Request

    curl 'https://sandbox.test.parku.io/v5/locations?sw=45.74001,5.67868&ne=47.74236,10.24900&date_start=2016&date_end=2016&filter_available=true&filter_bookable=true&filter_type=airport-parking&filter_price=&filter_properties=indoor&fields=all' \
    --insecure \
    --user 012345678abcdef:parku
    Headers
    Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencode
    Authorization: Basic MDEyMzQ1Njc4YWJjZGVmOnBhcmt1

    Example Response

    200

    Response Attributes
    locations
    array 

    locations[].id
    string Example: e644e4bc-4c5c-11e4-a24a-d43d7eecedd2

    unique identifier of the location used for referencing.

    locations[].address_slug
    string Example: dorfstrasse-11

    locations[].latitude
    number Example: 52.60826

    latitude part of the location geo coordinate

    locations[].longitude
    number Example: 13.19988

    longitude part of the location geo

    locations[].street
    string Example: Dorfstraße

    the street name of the location without number

    locations[].street_number
    string Example: 11

    the street number of the location

    locations[].postcode
    string Example: 16761

    post code of the location

    locations[].city
    string Example: Hennigsdorf

    city of the location

    locations[].country
    string Example: Deutschland

    country of the location in 2 character encoding country of the location in 2

    character encoding

    locations[].bookable
    boolean Example: true

    true if that locations can be booked via the parku API, false if the location

    is purely providing information

    locations[].payment
    object 

    available payment methods and types for the current user in this location. The payment methods and types depend on the private key of the logged in user. For locations requests using public keys these arrays will be empty.

    locations[].payment.methods
    array Example: [paypal]

    May Contain: paypal credits coupon braintree ideal

    Possible payment methods for this location and user

    locations[].payment.types
    array Example: [post]

    May Contain: post immediate

    Possible payment types for this location and user

    locations[].availability
    object 

    describes the availability of the location in relation to the request

    locations[].availability.current
    number Example: 0

    the number of parking spaces available in the group for the requested time period defined

    by start and endthe number of parking spaces available in the group for the requested time period defined by start and end

    locations[].availability.maximum
    number Example: 1

    the overall number of parking spaces at this group the overall number of parking spaces at

    this group

    locations[].availability.next_start
    string Example: 2016-...15:00:..

    the start of the next from now slot in which a parking space in this

    group is free and bookable, can be in the past

    locations[].availability.next_end
    string Example: 2016-...15:00:..

    the end of the next slot from now in which a parking space in this group

    is free and bookable, can be in the past

    locations[].parking_space_groups
    array 

    different parking space groups for this location. See Parking Space Group Data

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].id
    string Example: 1644c5dc-4c5c-11e4-a24a-d43d7eecedd2

    unique identifier of the location used for referencing.

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].type
    string Example: off-street

    Choices: off-street park-and-ride professional-garage airport-parking harbor-parking

    describes the type of location and can be one of the following.

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].description
    string Example: Doppelparkplatz. Jedoch nur für ein Auto zu vermieten.

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].image_urls
    array Example: [https://parku.de/images/parkingspace/020a81f5-c8b9-11e4-bfd2-d43d7eece658/640x286.jpg]

    urls of location images, can be empty

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].options
    array Example: [excess length]

    May Contain: excess length indoor disabled patio barrier charging station key_necessary long_term_booking surveillance valet_service

    describes which options are available at the location and can contains each of the following elements. The list can be empty.

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].support
    object 

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].price
    object 

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].user_owned
    boolean Example: false

    true if the user who requested the location is also the owner of the parking space. This allows to determine if the user could block the parking space from bookings.

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].settings
    object 

    provides booking requirements for the location. The settings of a location are used in favor of the global settings that can be found in the settings endpoint.

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].required_fields
    array Example: [car_registration_number]

    May Contain: car_registration_number car_make car_model car_colour number_of_passengers car_dropoff_time car_pickup_time outbound_flight_terminal outbound_flight_number inbound_flight_number outbound_flight_time inbound_flight_time user_mobile_number ship_name pier_name child_seat_required additional_services inbound_flight_terminal

    lists all additionally required fields when creating a booking for this location, can be empty if no fields are required. The field names correspond to the booking.fields.* entries in the settings endpoint which can be used for retrieving translated strings for these fields.

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].provider
    string Example: parku

    Choices: parku holidayextras inrix

    names the parking space provider. Additional information(terms and conditions, logo, …) about the provider can found be using the provider key from the field in settings

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].availability
    object 

    describes the availability of the group in relation to the requestdescribes the

    availability of the group in relation to the request

    locations[].gates
    array 

    the gates connected to the location

    locations[].gates[].type
    string Example: qrcode

    Choices: qrcode beacon

    the type how the gate can be opened

    locations[].gates[].identifier
    string Example: PARKU3KU

    the identifier for the access method, a short identification string for qrcode and the bluetooth id for beacon

    locations[].gates[].gateways
    array

    List Locations ¶
    GET/locations{?sw,ne,date_start,date_end,filter_available,filter_bookable,filter_type,filter_price,filter_properties,fields}

    Returns a list of locations for a given bounding box. This request returns the highest ranking 42 locations in the bounding box and does not return any other locations if there are more than 42. For retrieving all locations in a hierarchical manner, you can use the List Clusters request.

    The parameters named filter_* filter the returned results using the following logic:

    available
AND bookable
AND (type1 OR type2 OR ...)
AND (price1 OR price2 OR ...)
AND (properties1 AND properties2 AND ...)
    URI Parameters
    sw
    string (required) Example: 45.74001,5.67868

    Comma separated latitude and longitude of the southwest position.

    ne
    string (required) Example: 47.74236,10.24900

    Comma separated latitude and longitude of the northeast position.

    date_start
    string (required) Example: 2016

    10-27T09:10:20+00:00 (ISO 8601, optional) - Filter parking spaces for the start date. date_start will have no effect unless date_end is also provided.

    date_end
    string (required) Example: 2016

    10-27T10:10:20+00:00 (ISO 8601, optional) - Filter parking spaces for the end date. date_end will have no effect unless date_start is also provided.

    filter_available
    boolean (optional) Default: false Example: true

    Filters returned locations regarding their availability if start and end are also given.

    • true only returns available locations

    • false return all locations

    Choices: true false

    filter_bookable
    boolean (optional) Example: true

    Filters returned locations regarding their general bookability.

    • true only returns locations that could be booked through the api if they are available

    • false only returns locations that can not be booked through the api, even though they might be available

    Choices: true false

    filter_type
    array[string] (optional) Example: airport-parking

    Filters the result to only show parking spaces with with either of the provided types.

    Choices: off-street park-and-ride professional-garage airport-parking harbor-parking

    filter_price
    array[string] (optional) 

    Filters the result to only show parking spaces with either of the provided rates.

    Choices: rate_hourly rate_daily rate_weekly rate_monthly

    filter_properties
    array[string] (optional) Example: indoor

    Filters the result to only show parking spaces all the provided properties.

    Choices: excess_length indoor patio disabled charging_station key_necessary long_term_booking surveillance valet_service barrier

    fields
    array[string] (optional) Example: all

    Response will only contain the fields mentioned in this parameter. This can either be all or an comma separated list of field names from the response, e.g. id,street,country.

    Example Request

    curl 'https://sandbox.test.parku.io/v5/locations/clusters?sw=45.74001,5.67868&ne=47.74236,10.24900&date_start=2016&date_end=2016&filter_available=true&filter_bookable=true&filter_type=airport-parking&filter_price=&filter_properties=indoor&fields=all' \
    --insecure \
    --user 012345678abcdef:parku
    Headers
    Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencode
    Authorization: Basic MDEyMzQ1Njc4YWJjZGVmOnBhcmt1

    Example Response

    200
    Headers
    Content-Type: application/json

    Response Attributes
    clusters
    array 

    A cluster contains meta information about the locations inside a specific area. The cluster itself contains 2 levels. The first level groups the second level clusters that are given by the field includes.

    First level clusters are great for display on maps as we make sure that those clusters have a certain distance to each other.

    Second level clusters are great for being displayed in a list as they all have a distinct name and a parent city/country that can be used for grouping them. These clusters work on 3 predefined levels: - postcode: contains only locations with same postcode - city: contains only locations in same city - country: contains only locations in same country Which level is returned depends on the bounding box size of your request.

    clusters[].title
    string Example: 13405

    clusters[].type
    string Example: postcode

    Choices: postcode city country

    clusters[].count
    number Example: 4

    The number of locations inside the cluster.

    clusters[].center_latitude
    number Example: 52.528809357143

    Latitude of the cluster center.

    clusters[].center_longitude
    number Example: 13.379654547619

    Longitude of the cluster center.

    clusters[].sw_latitude
    number Example: 52.505681

    South west corner latitude of the cluster bounding boxes.

    clusters[].sw_longitude
    number Example: 13.285105

    South west corner longitude of the cluster bounding boxes.

    clusters[].ne_latitude
    number Example: 52.576979

    North east corner latitude of the cluster bounding boxes.

    clusters[].ne_longitude
    number Example: 13.47168

    North east corner longitude of the cluster bounding boxes.

    clusters[].includes
    array 

    List of second level clusters contained in this cluster.

    clusters[].includes[].title
    string Example: 10115

    clusters[].includes[].type
    string Example: postcode

    Choices: postcode city country

    clusters[].includes[].count
    number Example: 4

    The number of locations inside the cluster.

    clusters[].includes[].center_latitude
    number Example: 52.528809357143

    Latitude of the cluster center.

    clusters[].includes[].center_longitude
    number Example: 13.379654547619

    Longitude of the cluster center.

    clusters[].includes[].sw_latitude
    number Example: 52.505681

    South west corner latitude of the cluster bounding boxes.

    clusters[].includes[].sw_longitude
    number Example: 13.285105

    South west corner longitude of the cluster bounding boxes.

    clusters[].includes[].ne_latitude
    number Example: 52.576979

    North east corner latitude of the cluster bounding boxes.

    clusters[].includes[].ne_longitude
    number Example: 13.47168

    North east corner longitude of the cluster bounding boxes.

    clusters[].includes[].city
    string Example: Berlin

    parent city the cluster belongs to, only shown if the cluster type is postcode

    clusters[].includes[].country
    string Example: Deutschland

    parent country the cluster belongs to, only shown if the cluster type is postcode or city

    post code of the location

    string Example: Deutschland

    country of the location in 2 character encoding country of the location in 2

    character encoding

    locations[].bookable
    boolean Example: true

    true if that locations can be booked via the parku API, false if the location

    is purely providing information

    locations[].payment
    object 

    available payment methods and types for the current user in this location. The payment methods and types depend on the private key of the logged in user. For locations requests using public keys these arrays will be empty.

    locations[].payment.methods
    array Example: [paypal]

    May Contain: paypal credits coupon braintree ideal

    Possible payment methods for this location and user

    locations[].payment.types
    array Example: [post]

    May Contain: post immediate

    Possible payment types for this location and user

    locations[].availability
    object 

    describes the availability of the location in relation to the request

    locations[].availability.current
    number Example: 0

    the number of parking spaces available in the group for the requested time period defined

    by start and endthe number of parking spaces available in the group for the requested time period defined by start and end

    locations[].availability.maximum
    number Example: 1

    the overall number of parking spaces at this group the overall number of parking spaces at

    this group

    locations[].availability.next_start
    string Example: 2016-...15:00:..

    the start of the next from now slot in which a parking space in this

    group is free and bookable, can be in the past

    locations[].availability.next_end
    string Example: 2016-...15:00:..

    the end of the next slot from now in which a parking space in this group

    is free and bookable, can be in the past

    locations[].parking_space_groups
    array 

    different parking space groups for this location. See Parking Space Group Data

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].id
    string Example: 1644c5dc-4c5c-11e4-a24a-d43d7eecedd2

    unique identifier of the location used for referencing.

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].type
    string Example: off-street

    Choices: off-street park-and-ride professional-garage airport-parking harbor-parking

    describes the type of location and can be one of the following.

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].description
    string Example: Doppelparkplatz. Jedoch nur für ein Auto zu vermieten.

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].image_urls
    array Example: [https://parku.de/images/parkingspace/020a81f5-c8b9-11e4-bfd2-d43d7eece658/640x286.jpg]

    urls of location images, can be empty

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].options
    array Example: [excess length]

    May Contain: excess length indoor disabled patio barrier charging station key_necessary long_term_booking surveillance valet_service

    describes which options are available at the location and can contains each of the following elements. The list can be empty.

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].support
    object 

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].price
    object 

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].user_owned
    boolean Example: false

    true if the user who requested the location is also the owner of the parking space. This allows to determine if the user could block the parking space from bookings.

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].settings
    object 

    provides booking requirements for the location. The settings of a location are used in favor of the global settings that can be found in the settings endpoint.

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].required_fields
    array Example: [car_registration_number]

    May Contain: car_registration_number car_make car_model car_colour number_of_passengers car_dropoff_time car_pickup_time outbound_flight_terminal outbound_flight_number inbound_flight_number outbound_flight_time inbound_flight_time user_mobile_number ship_name pier_name child_seat_required additional_services inbound_flight_terminal

    lists all additionally required fields when creating a booking for this location, can be empty if no fields are required. The field names correspond to the booking.fields.* entries in the settings endpoint which can be used for retrieving translated strings for these fields.

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].provider
    string Example: parku

    Choices: parku holidayextras inrix

    names the parking space provider. Additional information(terms and conditions, logo, …) about the provider can found be using the provider key from the field in settings

    locations[].parking_space_groups[].availability
    object 

    describes the availability of the group in relation to the requestdescribes the

    availability of the group in relation to the request

    the gates connected to the location

    Choices: qrcode beacon

    the type how the gate can be opened

    locations[].gates[].identifier
    string Example: PARKU3KU

    the identifier for the access method, a short identification string for qrcode and the bluetooth id for beacon

    locations[].gates[].gateways
    array

    List Clusters ¶
    GET/locations/clusters{?sw,ne,date_start,date_end,filter_available,filter_bookable,filter_type,filter_price,filter_properties,fields}

    Returns a list of locations and clusters. Clusters are returned if there are too many locations to return for a specific part of the bounding box. You have to execute multiple hierarchical requests to get all locations from the clusters.

    The parameters named filter_* filter the returned results using the following logic:

    available
AND bookable
AND (type1 OR type2 OR ...)
AND (price1 OR price2 OR ...)
AND (properties1 AND properties2 AND ...)
    URI Parameters
    sw
    string (required) Example: 45.74001,5.67868

    Comma separated latitude and longitude of the southwest position.

    ne
    string (required) Example: 47.74236,10.24900

    Comma separated latitude and longitude of the northeast position.

    date_start
    string (required) Example: 2016

    10-27T09:10:20+00:00 (ISO 8601, optional) - Filter parking spaces for the start date. date_start will have no effect unless date_end is also provided.

    date_end
    string (required) Example: 2016

    10-27T10:10:20+00:00 (ISO 8601, optional) - Filter parking spaces for the end date. date_end will have no effect unless date_start is also provided.

    filter_available
    boolean (optional) Default: false Example: true

    Filters returned locations regarding their availability if start and end are also given.

    • true only returns available locations

    • false return all locations

    Choices: true false

    filter_bookable
    boolean (optional) Example: true

    Filters returned locations regarding their general bookability.

    • true only returns locations that could be booked through the api if they are available

    • false only returns locations that can not be booked through the api, even though they might be available

    Choices: true false

    filter_type
    array[string] (optional) Example: airport-parking

    Filters the result to only show parking spaces with with either of the provided types.

    Choices: off-street park-and-ride professional-garage airport-parking harbor-parking

    filter_price
    array[string] (optional) 

    Filters the result to only show parking spaces with either of the provided rates.

    Choices: rate_hourly rate_daily rate_weekly rate_monthly

    filter_properties
    array[string] (optional) Example: indoor

    Filters the result to only show parking spaces all the provided properties.

    Choices: excess_length indoor patio disabled charging_station key_necessary long_term_booking surveillance valet_service barrier

    fields
    array[string] (optional) Example: all

    Response will only contain the fields mentioned in this parameter. This can either be all or an comma separated list of field names from the response, e.g. id,street,country.

    Example Request

    curl 'https://sandbox.test.parku.io/v5/locations/00cd7cfd-e42d-11e2-8bf1-8a83f3373875/availability?date_start=2016&date_end=2016' \
    --insecure \
    --user 012345678abcdef:parku
    Headers
    Authorization: Basic MDEyMzQ1Njc4YWJjZGVmOnBhcmt1

    Example Response

    200

    Displays the availability times. For every affected availability period there will be one entry in the json. This sub json contains 9 keys, one for every weekday including the day’s times and also the period start and end. weekday_1 is a Monday.

    Caution: This does not include bookings

    A period is affected, if one of the following holds:

    • date_start is between period start and period end

    • date_end is between period start and end

    • date_start and date_end overlay the period

    Body
    {
  "begin": "2016-04-09T00:00:00+02:00",
  "end": "2016-04-18T00:00:00+02:00",
  "weekday_1": [
    {
      "start": "08:00",
      "end": "17:00"
    }
  ],
  "weekday_2": [
    {
      "start": "08:00",
      "end": "17:00"
    }
  ],
  "weekday_3": [
    {
      "start": "08:00",
      "end": "16:00"
    }
  ],
  "weekday_4": [
    {
      "start": "08:00",
      "end": "16:00"
    }
  ],
  "weekday_5": [
    {
      "start": "08:00",
      "end": "18:00"
    }
  ],
  "weekday_6": [
    {
      "start": "08:00",
      "end": "17:00"
    }
  ],
  "weekday_7": [
    {
      "start": "08:00",
      "end": "17:00"
    }
  ]
}

    Get availability times for location ¶
    GET/locations/{location_id}/availability{?date_start,date_end}

    URI Parameters
    location_id
    uuid rfc4122 (required) Example: 00cd7cfd-e42d-11e2-8bf1-8a83f3373875

    Identifier of the location.

    date_start
    string (required) Example: 2016

    10-27T09:10:20+00:00 (ISO 8601, optional) - Start of time frame to include periods. If date_start is provided, date_end is required and vice versa.

    date_end
    string (required) Example: 2016

    10-27T10:10:20+00:00 (ISO 8601, optional) see date_start.

    Example Request

    curl 'https://sandbox.test.parku.io/v5/locations/00cd7cfd-e42d-11e2-8bf1-8a83f3373875/terms' \
    --insecure \
    --user 012345678abcdef:parku
    Headers
    Authorization: Basic MDEyMzQ1Njc4YWJjZGVmOnBhcmt1

    Example Response

    200
    Headers
    Content-Type: application/xhtml+xml
    Body
    <!DOCTYPE html>
  <html xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"...

    Retrieve Terms and Conditions ¶
    GET/locations/{location_id}/terms

    Deprecated This endpoint is deprecated. /settings endpoint should be used instead.

    Each location can have different terms and conditions. With this endpoint you can retrieve location based terms and conditions.

    URI Parameters
    location_id
    uuid rfc4122 (required) Example: 00cd7cfd-e42d-11e2-8bf1-8a83f3373875

    Identifier of the location.

    Login ¶

    Login ¶

    Access needs a public key.

    --request POST \
    --user 012345678abcdef:parku \
    -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
    -d @- << EOF
    {
      "email": "test@example.com",
      "password": "1234pwd"

    Login ¶
    POST/login

    Checks the given credentials email and password for validity. Returns the user object with a user token needed for private endpoints. A public key is needed. All further requests using the token as HTTP Basic Auth username are made on behalf of the user.

    Login through Facebook is described in a separate endpoint.

    Request Attributes
    email
    string (required) Example: test@example.com

    The users email address.

    password
    string (required) Example: 1234pwd

    The users password.

    Retrieve Onstreet Zone Information ¶
    GET/onstreet{?lat,lon}

    Access needs at least a public key.

    This request returns parking zone information about a specific point on the map.

    URI Parameters
    lat
    number (required) Example: 53.12341234

    latitude of the requested point

    lon
    number (required) Example: 13.12341234

    longitude of the requested point

    Example Request

    curl 'https://sandbox.test.parku.io/v5/onstreet/start' \
    --insecure \
    --request POST \
    -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
    -d @- << EOF
    {
      "zone": {
        "id": "101012",
        "latitude": 53.12341234,
        "longitude": 13.12341234
      },
      "payment_method": {
        "id": "1000bb3e-506d-11e5-9781-d43d7eece658",
        "type": "immediate"
      },
      "license_plate": "AB 1234",
      "phone_number": "01234567890",
      "duration_minutes": 15,
      "user_metadata": {
        "latitude": 52.521381,
        "longitude": 13.3920158
      }
    }
    EOF
    Headers
    Content-Type: application/json

      "type": "string",
      "description": "the customer phone number"
    },
    "duration_minutes": {
      "type": "number",
      "description": "the parking duration, required if the retrieved zone had entries in the `available_durations` field."
    },
    "user_metadata": {
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "latitude": {
          "type": "number",
          "description": "users latitude"
        },
        "longitude": {
          "type": "number",
          "description": "users longitude"
        }
      },
      "description": "Additional information about a user (optional). This is for example latitude/longitude parameters\nfor the users current position."
    }
  },
  "required": [
    "zone",
    "payment_method",
    "license_plate",
    "phone_number"
  ],
  "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-04/schema#"
}

    character encoding

    location.bookable
    boolean Example: true

    true if that locations can be booked via the parku API, false if the location

    is purely providing information

    location.payment
    object 

    available payment methods and types for the current user in this location. The payment methods and types depend on the private key of the logged in user. For locations requests using public keys these arrays will be empty.

    location.payment.methods
    array Example: [paypal]

    May Contain: paypal credits coupon braintree ideal

    Possible payment methods for this location and user

    location.payment.types
    array Example: [post]

    May Contain: post immediate

    Possible payment types for this location and user

    shows the price per month

    location.parking_space_groups[].user_owned
    boolean Example: false

    true if the user who requested the location is also the owner of the parking space. This allows to determine if the user could block the parking space from bookings.

    location.parking_space_groups[].settings
    object 

    provides booking requirements for the location. The settings of a location are used in favor of the global settings that can be found in the settings endpoint.

    location.parking_space_groups[].settings.bookable_range_start

    start of the range wherein a booking is allowed in minutes from now.

    location.parking_space_groups[].settings.bookable_range_end
    number Example: 43200

    location.parking_space_groups[].settings.booking_duration_max
    number Example: 43200

    maximum duration of a booking in minutes.

    location.parking_space_groups[].required_fields
    array Example: [car_registration_number]

    May Contain: car_registration_number car_make car_model car_colour number_of_passengers car_dropoff_time car_pickup_time outbound_flight_terminal outbound_flight_number inbound_flight_number outbound_flight_time inbound_flight_time user_mobile_number ship_name pier_name child_seat_required additional_services inbound_flight_terminal

    lists all additionally required fields when creating a booking for this location, can be empty if no fields are required. The field names correspond to the booking.fields.* entries in the settings endpoint which can be used for retrieving translated strings for these fields.

    object (required)

    string Example: 15 Min. gebührenfrei, danach 50 Cent pro 30 Min.

    description of the price

    zone.price.currency
    string Example: EUR

    Choices: EUR CHF

    the currency of the price

    zone.max_datetime_end
    string Example: 2009-06-30T18:30:00+02:00

    Latest time when a booking has to end. Bookings that are not stopped after this time will be automatically stopped on backend side.

    zone.duration_max_minutes`
    number Example: 760

    Maximum time the booking can be running in minutes. Bookings that are not stopped after this amount of time will be automatically stopped on backend side.

    Start an Onstreet Booking ¶
    POST/onstreet/start

    Access needs at least a private key.

    Bookings can be stopped using the Stop a Booking action.

    The request requires some of the values that were received by the Retrieve Onstreet Zone Information request. These values are checked against the booking that is started with the onstreet provider to ensure that the pricing is as expected. The optional attributes of the parking zone object here are mainly used for logging.

    Request Attributes  (application/json)
    zone
    object (required) 

    the parking zone object to start the booking on

    zone.id
    string (required) Example: 101012

    the parking zone id

    zone.latitude
    number (required) Example: 53.12341234

    latitude of the requested point

    zone.longitude
    number (required) Example: 13.12341234

    longitude of the requested point

    payment_method
    object (required) 

    information about payment method.

    payment_method.id
    string (optional) Example: 1000bb3e-506d-11e5-9781-d43d7eece658

    the payment method id,

    only needed if type is immediate

    payment_method.type
    string (required) Example: immediate

    Choices: immediate

    How to execute the payment. Currently only immediate

    payments are supported.

    license_plate
    string (required) Example: AB 1234

    the license plate of the car used for parking

    phone_number
    string (required) Example: 01234567890

    the customer phone number

    duration_minutes
    number (optional) Example: 15

    the parking duration, required if the retrieved zone had entries in the available_durations field.

    user_metadata
    object 

    Additional information about a user (optional). This is for example latitude/longitude parameters for the users current position.

    user_metadata.latitude
    number (optional) Example: 52.521381

    users latitude

    user_metadata.longitude
    number (optional) Example: 13.3920158

    users longitude

    Password ¶

    Password ¶

    Example Request

    curl 'https://sandbox.test.parku.io/v5/password' \
    --insecure \
    --request PUT \
    --user 012345678abcdef:parku \
    -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
    -d @- << EOF
    {
      "old_password": "pwd123",
      "new_password": "pwd321"
    }
    EOF
    Headers
    Authorization: Basic MDEyMzQ1Njc4YWJjZGVmOnBhcmt1
    Body
    {
  "old_password": "pwd123",
  "new_password": "pwd321"
}
    Schema
    {
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "old_password": {
      "type": "string",
      "description": "The current active password."
    },
    "new_password": {
      "type": "string",
      "description": "The new password."
    }
  },
  "required": [
    "old_password",
    "new_password"
  ],
  "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-04/schema#"
}

    Example Response

    204
    This response has no content.

    Update password ¶
    PUT/password

    Access needs a private key.

    Request Attributes
    old_password
    string (required) Example: pwd123

    The current active password.

    new_password
    string (required) Example: pwd321

    The new password.

    Example Request

    curl 'https://sandbox.test.parku.io/v5/password?for=test@example.com' \
    --insecure \
    --user 012345678abcdef:parku
    Headers
    Authorization: Basic MDEyMzQ1Njc4YWJjZGVmOnBhcmt1

    Example Response

    204404
    This response has no content.

    The given email address is not found in the database.

    Reset password ¶
    GET/password{?for}

    Access needs a public key.

    This sends an email with the newly set password to the users email address.

    URI Parameters
    for
    string (required) Example: test@example.com

    A valid email address of the user.

    List all Phone Numbers ¶
    GET/phone_numbers

    Returns a list of all phone numbers of the user. The phone numbers are returned sorted by creation date, with the most recently created phone number appearing first.

    Example Request

    curl 'https://sandbox.test.parku.io/v5/phone_numbers' \
    --insecure \
    --request POST \
    --user 012345678abcdef:parku \
    -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
    -d @- << EOF
    {
      "phone_number": "+493057701873"
    }
    EOF
    Headers
    Content-Type: application/json
    Authorization: Basic MDEyMzQ1Njc4YWJjZGVmOnBhcmt1
    Body
    {
  "phone_number": "+493057701873"
}
    Schema
    {
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "phone_number": {
      "type": "string",
      "description": "The phone number."
    }
  },
  "required": [
    "phone_number"
  ],
  "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-04/schema#"
}

    Example Response

    201
    Headers
    Content-Type: application/json
    Body
    {
  "id": "151",
  "phone_number": "+493057701873"
}

    Prices ¶

    All fields that are money value related are given as integer values. Typically this is user credits, amounts in payments, booking prices and location prices. If not otherwise stated, these prices are converted to float values using an exponent of -2: float_value = int_value * 10 ^ (-2)

    Sesam ¶

    Access needs a private key.

    Sesam Actions ¶

    This endpoint is used to open gates and barriers. A private key is needed. The user scans a QR code which is attached somewhere near the gate or barrier. The QR code contains an URL: http://parku.ch/s/1234abcd or http://parku.de/s/1234abcd.

    The part after the last / (slash) represents the sesam ID. You have to parse the URL and create an API call with the sesam ID.

    Both QR codes are valid and activate a sesam device in the parku office.

    Example Request

    curl 'https://sandbox.test.parku.io/v5/sesam/1234abcd' \
    --insecure \
    --request PUT \
    --user 012345678abcdef:parku
    Headers
    Authorization: Basic MDEyMzQ1Njc4YWJjZGVmOnBhcmt1

    Example Response

    204404401

    Everything went fine. The gate/barrier connected to the sesam device should open in the next few seconds.

    The QR code is not valid. Either it is not a parku QR code or the QR code is outdated.

    The code is valid, but the user does not have the permissions to use this sesam device. Either no booking is made or the time for opening the sesam has expired.

    Open Sesam ¶
    PUT/sesam/{sesam_id}

    URI Parameters
    sesam_id
    string (required) Example: 1234abcd

    The sesam ID which is hidden in the QR code.

    Sesam ¶

    Example Request

    curl 'https://sandbox.test.parku.io/v5/sesam' \
    --insecure \
    --user 012345678abcdef:parku
    Headers
    Authorization: Basic MDEyMzQ1Njc4YWJjZGVmOnBhcmt1

    Example Response

    200404

    Returned if a booking with a sesam device is available.

    Headers
    Content-Type: application/json
    Body
    {
  "support": {
    "phone_number": {
      "phone_number": "+49 123 456 789"
    }
  }
}

    No booking with a sesam device available.

    Check Sesam ¶
    GET/sesam

    This endpoint gives you the information whether the user can open a sesam device now or in the near future.

    Response Attributes
    location
    object 

    provides the booking requirements for a parking space.

    Every location can have its own settings but these will always be the same or within the limits of the global settings.

    location.bookable_range_start
    number Example: -15

    start of the range wherein a booking is allowed in minutes from now.

    location.bookable_range_end
    number Example: 43200

    end of the range wherein a booking is allowed in minutes from now.

    location.booking_duration_min
    number Example: 30

    minimum duration of a booking in minutes.

    location.booking_duration_max
    number Example: 43200

    maximum duration of a booking in minutes.

    sesam
    object 

    contains informations about how to work with the sesam boxes.

    sesam.bluetooth
    object 

    sesam.bluetooth.connection_trials
    number Example: 2

    Amount of tries to connect to a sesam box.

    sesam.bluetooth.connection_timeout
    number Example: 2

    Amount of seconds allowed to connect to a box.

    sesam.bluetooth.communication_timeout
    number Example: 2

    Second until canceling the communication with the sesam box.

    gps
    object 

    contains information on how to handle GPS data.

    gps.ttl
    number Example: 60

    Time-To-Live for previously retrieved GPS data i.e. by operation system

    gps.accuracy
    number Example: 1000

    Accuracy of GPS data in meters, renders data invalid if exceeded

    booking
    object 

    contains information on how to handle bookings.

    booking.collection

    string Example: zusätzliche Dienste

    string Example: text

    Choices: text datetime date time number tel boolean

    features
    object 

    Feature flags that enables or disables certaint features based parameters given in header. These feature flags can be different for each operation systems.

    features.recommend_update
    object 

    features.recommend_update.enabled
    boolean Example: true

    defines wether the flag is enabled

    features.force_update
    object 

    features.force_update.enabled
    boolean Example: true

    defines wether the flag is enabled

    features.non_bookable_ps_visible
    object 

    features.non_bookable_ps_visible.enabled
    boolean Example: true

    defines wether the flag is enabled

    features.smart_device_link_enabled
    object 

    features.smart_device_link_enabled.enabled
    boolean Example: true

    defines wether the flag is enabled

    provider
    object 

    Information for parking space provider. Key is linked with location response field provider.

    provider.image
    string Example: http://provider/image.png

    Large provider logo.

    provider.thumbnail
    string Example: http://provider/thumbnail.png

    Provider logo thumbnail.

    provider.header
    string Example: Please provide the data necessary for booking the parking space.

    Translated header text for required fields.

    provider.legals
    object 

    Contains two lists for terms and conditions entries where you can find text and url for each.

    provider.legals.accept
    object 

    List of terms and conditions entries which the user needs to accept by some action (like checkbox).

    provider.legals.accept.url
    string Example: http://www.provider.com/terms_and_conditions.html

    link to terms and conditions

    provider.legals.accept.text
    string Example: Please accept the parking providers' %TERMS_LINK%.

    prompt for accepting the terms and conditions. Replace %TERMS_LINK% with the url

    provider.legals.show
    object 

    List of terms and conditions entries which the user needs only to see.

    provider.legals.show.url
    string Example: http://www.provider.com/terms_and_conditions.html

    link to terms and conditions

    provider.legals.show.text
    string Example: Please accept the parking providers' %TERMS_LINK%.

    prompt for accepting the terms and conditions. Replace %TERMS_LINK% with the url

    Retrieve Settings ¶
    GET/settings{?lat,lon}

    This endpoint exposes the global settings for the ParkU-platform. Changing the settings is not possible.

    URI Parameters
    lat
    float (optional) Example: 52.53568811

    Latitude of current location.

    lon
    float (optional) Example: 13.39412887

    Longitude of current location.

    Notification ¶

    Example Request

    curl 'https://sandbox.test.parku.io/v5/settings/booking/notification/entry' \
    --insecure \
    --request PUT \
    --user 012345678abcdef:parku \
    -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
    -d @- << EOF
    {
      "enabled": true
    }
    EOF
    Headers
    Content-Type: application/json
    Authorization: Basic MDEyMzQ1Njc4YWJjZGVmOnBhcmt1
    Body
    {
  "enabled": true
}
    Schema
    {
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "enabled": {
      "type": "boolean",
      "description": "The value for the notification key."
    }
  },
  "required": [
    "enabled"
  ],
  "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-04/schema#"
}

    Example Response

    204304

    Updated successfully.

    Value of notification was not modified.

    Enable/Disable Notification ¶

    Request Attributes  (application/json)

    enum (required) Example: entry

    A notification key

    Choices: time_to_leave near_location entry expiring over

    Update a user ¶
    PUT/user

    Access needs a private key.

    Updates the user by setting the values of the parameters passed. Any parameters not provided will be left unchanged.

    This request accepts mostly the same arguments as the user creation call. Changing cars, phone_numbers, attributes and password is done via separate endpoints.

    Request Attributes  (application/json)
    email
    string (optional) Example: test@example.com

    password
    string (optional) Example: test

    country
    string (optional) Example: DE

    Choices: DE CH

    firstname
    string (optional) Example: Max

    lastname
    string (optional) Example: Power

    gender
    string (optional) Example: female

    Choices: female male

    age_range
    string (optional) Example: 18 - 25

    Choices: 18 - 25 26 - 35 36 - 45 46+

    Access needs a private key.

    Example Request

    curl 'https://sandbox.test.parku.io/v5/user/payment_methods' \

    Headers

    Response Attributes
    .[].id
    string Example: 1000bb3e-506d-11e5-9781-d43d7eece658

    the payment method id

    .[].created_at
    string Example: 2009-06-30T18:30:00+02:00

    date when the payment method was created

    .[].post_payment
    boolean Example: false

    wether this payment method is usable for post payments

    .[].primary
    boolean Example: true

    wether this is the primary payment method of the user

    .[].validated
    string Example: successful

    Choices: successful failed pending

    Wether the payment method was already validated successfully. Non validated payment methods cannot be used for paying.

    .[].provider_type
    string Example: stripe

    Choices: stripe

    provider type

    .[].provider
    object 

    payment using stripe

    .[].provider.customer_id
    string Example: cus_123456789

    stripe customer id

    .[].provider.source_id
    string Example: card_123456789

    stripe source id

    .[].provider.instrument_type
    string Example: credit_card

    type of payment instrument used for charging

    .[].provider.instrument
    object 

    the credit card information

    .[].provider.instrument.number
    string Example: 6789

    last 4 digits of credit card

    .[].provider.instrument.type
    string Example: Visa

    card type as defined by brand at https://stripe.com/docs/api#card_object

    .[].provider.instrument.expire_month
    number Example: 12

    expiration month of the credit card

    .[].provider.instrument.expire_year
    number Example: 2067

    expiration year of the credit card

    .[].provider.instrument.country
    string Example: DE

    two letter ISO code representing the country of the card

    .[].provider.instrument.cvc_check
    string Example: pass

    Choices: pass fail unavailable unchecked

    result of the cvc check if cvc was provided

    .[].fee
    object 

    .[].fee.percent
    number Example: 1.4

    the payment provider fee percentage. This percentage is added on top of the overall booking cost. The overall booking cost is calculated by booking_fee + booking_fee * fee_percentage + fee_fixed.

    .[].fee.fixed
    number Example: 25

    fixed payment provider fee.

    .[].fee.minimum_total
    number Example: 50

    minimum total amount for a booking transaction. If a booking is cheaper than this, the payment provider fee will be adapted.

    List user payment methods ¶
    GET/user/payment_methods

    Example Request

    curl 'https://sandbox.test.parku.io/v5/user/payment_methods/primary' \
    --insecure \
    --user 012345678abcdef:parku
    Headers
    Content-Type: application/
    Authorization: Basic MDEyMzQ1Njc4YWJjZGVmOnBhcmt1

    Retrieve primary payment method ¶
    GET/user/payment_methods/primary

    Example Request

    curl 'https://sandbox.test.parku.io/v5/user/payment_methods' \
    --insecure \
    --request POST \
    --user 012345678abcdef:parku \
    -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
    -d @- << EOF
    {
      "primary": true,
      "provider_type": "stripe",
      "provider": {
        "source_id": "tok_1234567890"
      }
    }
    EOF
    Headers
    Content-Type: application/json
    Authorization: Basic MDEyMzQ1Njc4YWJjZGVmOnBhcmt1
    Body
    {
  "primary": true,
  "provider_type": "stripe",
  "provider": {
    "source_id": "tok_1234567890"
  }
}
    Schema
    {
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "primary": {
      "type": "boolean",
      "default": false,
      "description": "Wether the payment method should be activated as the users primary payment method.\nIf another payment method of the user was set to be the primary method before,\nthat one will be be changed to not be the primary one anymore."
    },
    "provider_type": {
      "enum": [
        "stripe"
      ],
      "description": "provider type"
    },
    "provider": {
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "source_id": {
          "type": "string",
          "description": "the stripe source token for a credit card or a token representing a credit\ncard as returned by various stripe libraries, see https://stripe.com/docs/checkout"
        }
      },
      "required": [
        "source_id"
      ],
      "description": "provider information"
    }
  },
  "allOf": [
    {
      "not": {
        "required": [
          "provider"
        ]
      }
    }
  ],
  "required": [
    "provider_type"
  ],
  "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-04/schema#"
}

    Add a user payment method ¶
    POST/user/payment_methods

    Adds a new payment method for the user.

    Request Attributes  (application/json)
    primary
    boolean (optional) Example: true

    Wether the payment method should be activated as the users primary payment method. If another payment method of the user was set to be the primary method before, that one will be be changed to not be the primary one anymore.

    provider_type
    string (required) Example: stripe

    Choices: stripe

    provider type

    provider
    object 

    provider information

    provider.source_id
    string (required) Example: tok_1234567890

    the stripe source token for a credit card or a token representing a credit card as returned by various stripe libraries, see https://stripe.com/docs/checkout

    Example Request

    curl 'https://sandbox.test.parku.io/v5/user/payment_methods/1000bb3e-506d-11e5-9781-d43d7eece658' \
    --insecure \
    --request PUT \
    --user 012345678abcdef:parku \
    -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
    -d @- << EOF
    {
      "primary": true
    }
    EOF
    Headers
    Content-Type: application/json
    Authorization: Basic MDEyMzQ1Njc4YWJjZGVmOnBhcmt1
    Body
    {
  "primary": true
}
    Schema
    {
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "primary": {
      "type": "boolean",
      "default": false,
      "description": "Wether the payment method should be activated as the users primary payment method.\nIf another payment method of the user was set to be the primary method before,\nthat one will be be changed to not be the primary one anymore."
    }
  },
  "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-04/schema#"
}

    Example Response

    200422

    Returned when the payment method was successfully activated/deactivated.

    Headers
    Content-Type: application/json
    Body
    {
  "id": "1000bb3e-506d-11e5-9781-d43d7eece658",

    string Example: Visa

    card type as defined by brand at https://stripe.com/docs/api#card_object

    number Example: 12

    expiration month of the credit card

    provider.instrument.expire_year
    number Example: 2067

    expiration year of the credit card

    provider.instrument.country
    string Example: DE

    two letter ISO code representing the country of the card

    provider.instrument.cvc_check
    string Example: pass

    Choices: pass fail unavailable unchecked

    result of the cvc check if cvc was provided

    fee
    object 

    fee.percent
    number Example: 1.4

    the payment provider fee percentage. This percentage is added on top of the overall booking cost. The overall booking cost is calculated by booking_fee + booking_fee * fee_percentage + fee_fixed.

    fee.fixed
    number Example: 25

    fixed payment provider fee.

    fee.minimum_total
    number Example: 50

    minimum total amount for a booking transaction. If a booking is cheaper than this, the payment provider fee will be adapted.

    Update a user payment method ¶
    PUT/user/payment_methods/{payment_method_id}

    Updates a users payment method.

    Request Attributes  (application/json)
    primary
    boolean (optional) Example: true

    Wether the payment method should be activated as the users primary payment method. If another payment method of the user was set to be the primary method before, that one will be be changed to not be the primary one anymore.

    URI Parameters
    payment_method_id
    uuid rfc4122 (required) Example: 1000bb3e-506d-11e5-9781-d43d7eece658

    the user id

    Example Request

    curl 'https://sandbox.test.parku.io/v5/user/payment_methods/1000bb3e-506d-11e5-9781-d43d7eece658' \
    --insecure \
    --request DELETE \
    --user 012345678abcdef:parku
    Headers
    Content-Type: application/json
    Authorization: Basic MDEyMzQ1Njc4YWJjZGVmOnBhcmt1

    Example Response

    204422

    Returned when the payment method was successfully deleted.

    Headers
    Content-Type: application/json

    Returned if an error occured, e.g. a booking exists that waits for a payment from this method.

    Headers
    Content-Type: application/json
    Body
    {
  "code": 1001,
  "message": "Error description."
}

    code

    Delete a user payment method ¶
    DELETE/user/payment_methods/{payment_method_id}

    Deletes a user payment method.

    uuid rfc4122 (required) Example: 1000bb3e-506d-11e5-9781-d43d7eece658

    the user id

    Violations ¶

    Violations ¶

    Access needs a private key.

    You can store one violation per booking. A violation report is done in two steps:

    1. Create a new violation
    2. Add a photo

    Example Request

    curl 'https://sandbox.test.parku.io/v5/bookings/0072c629-e622-11e2-8bf1-8a83f3373875/violation' \
    --insecure \
    --request POST \
    --user 012345678abcdef:parku \
    -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
    -d @- << EOF
    {
      "license_plate": "B-CD 4321",
      "comment": "This car parked on my parking space!!!"
    }
    EOF
    Headers
    Content-Type: application/json
    Authorization: Basic MDEyMzQ1Njc4YWJjZGVmOnBhcmt1
    Body
    {
  "license_plate": "B-CD 4321",
  "comment": "This car parked on my parking space!!!"
}
    Schema
    {
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "license_plate": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "comment": {
      "type": "string"
    }
  },
  "required": [
    "license_plate",
    "comment"
  ],
  "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-04/schema#"
}

    Example Response

    200
    Headers
    Content-Type: application/json
    Body
    {
  "license_plate": "B-CD 4321",
  "comment": "This car parked on my parking space!!!",
  "image_url": null
}

    Create a New Violation ¶
    POST/bookings/{booking_id}/violation

    Request Attributes  (application/json)
    license_plate
    string (required) Example: B-CD 4321

    comment
    string (required) Example: This car parked on my parking space!!!

    URI Parameters
    booking_id
    uuid rfc4122 (required) Example: 0072c629-e622-11e2-8bf1-8a83f3373875

    The identifier of the booking to which the violation belongs to.

    Example Request

    curl 'https://sandbox.test.parku.io/v5/bookings/0072c629-e622-11e2-8bf1-8a83f3373875/violation' \
    --insecure \
    --user 012345678abcdef:parku
    Headers
    Authorization: Basic MDEyMzQ1Njc4YWJjZGVmOnBhcmt1

    Example Response

    200
    Headers
    Content-Type: application/json
    Body
    {
  "license_plate": "B-CD 4321",
  "comment": "This car parked on my parking space!!!",
  "image_url": "https://parku.ch/images/reports/12.jpeg"
}

    Update a Violation ¶
    PUT/bookings/{booking_id}/violation

    Updates the violation by setting the values of the parameters passed. Any parameters not provided will be left unchanged. The photo can be updated through adding a new photo.

    Request Attributes  (application/json)
    license_plate
    string (required) Example: B-CD 4321

    comment
    string (required) Example: This car parked on my parking space!!!

    URI Parameters
    booking_id
    uuid rfc4122 (required) Example: 0072c629-e622-11e2-8bf1-8a83f3373875

    The identifier of the booking to which the violation belongs to.

    Example Request

    curl 'https://sandbox.test.parku.io/v5/bookings/0072c629-e622-11e2-8bf1-8a83f3373875/violation' \
    --insecure \
    --request DELETE \
    --user 012345678abcdef:parku
    Headers
    Content-Type: application/json
    Authorization: Basic MDEyMzQ1Njc4YWJjZGVmOnBhcmt1

    Example Response

    204
    This response has no content.

    Example Request

  "comment": "This car parked on my parking space!!!",
  "image_url": "https://parku.ch/images/reports/12.jpeg"
}

    Add a Photo ¶
    PUT/bookings/{booking_id}/violation/image

    You can add one photo to the violation. If you add a new photo the previous one gets overwritten.

    The entire PUT body will be treated as the file. Make sure to add the Content-Type: application/octet-stream to your header.

    URI Parameters
    booking_id
    uuid rfc4122 (required) Example: 0072c629-e622-11e2-8bf1-8a83f3373875

    The identifier of the booking to which the violation belongs to.
